Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: My motivation stems from the critical challenge in federated learning (FL) for safety-critical applications like autonomous driving: not all clients contribute equally to global model performance. Some clients possess low-quality, non-representative, or inefficient data—either due to poor sensor calibration, rare driving conditions, or limited diversity—leading to noisy or misleading gradient updates. While existing works explore relevance filtering (Paper 1), client availability robustness (Paper 2), and influence estimation (Paper 3), none dynamically identify *data-inefficient* clients in real-time within high-stakes, simulation-based FL environments where data distribution shifts rapidly and model convergence must be both fast and reliable. The key insight is that inefficiency isn’t just about data irrelevance—it’s about the *utility* of a client’s update relative to its data cost (e.g., number of samples used per unit improvement). By integrating meta-learning principles with online influence tracking, we can build a system that learns to evaluate update efficiency on-the-fly, without accessing raw data. This differs from prior work by shifting focus from static relevance or availability to *dynamic utility assessment*, enabling adaptive exclusion of clients whose marginal gains fall below a learned threshold. Unlike Fed-Influence (Paper 3), which measures parameter-level impact, our method evaluates *efficiency-aware influence*: how much accuracy gain a client provides per unit of communication and local computation. This is especially vital in autonomous driving simulations, where thousands of agents generate heterogeneous driving logs under varying weather, traffic, and road conditions—some inherently less transferable than others.

